{"title_page": "Indiana University School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI", "text_new": "{{Primary sources|date=March 2010}}\n{{Infobox university\n|image_name = \n|name = Indiana University School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI\n|established = 1972\n|type = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|dean= William Blomquist\n|city = [[Indianapolis, IN|Indianapolis]]\n|state = [[Indiana]]\n|country = [[United States|USA]]\n|coor    = {{coord|39.773741|-86.175239|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|students = 2000\n|faculty= 230\n|website= [http://liberalarts.iupui.edu/ liberalarts.iupui.edu]\n}}\n\nThe '''Indiana University School of Liberal Arts''' is the home of the [[humanities]] and [[social sciences]] at [[Indiana University]]-[[Purdue University]] [[Indianapolis]] (IUPUI), an urban, research [[campus]]. The only [[liberal arts]] school in the Indiana University system, the School of Liberal Arts has 11 departments (Anthropology, Communication Studies, Economics, English, Geography, History, Philosophy, Political Science, Religious Studies, Sociology, and World Languages & Cultures), 16 undergraduate degree programs (including those offered in departmental disciplines as well as American Sign Language/English Interpreting, International Studies, Philanthropic Studies and the Individualized Major Program), and 15 graduate degrees and certificates including Ph.D.s in Economics and Philanthropic Studies. The School of Liberal Arts also houses multiple centers for research and study, some nationally and internationally renowned.\n\n[[File:IUPUI-Cavanaugh-trees.JPG|thumb|Cavanaugh Hall is home to the IU School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI.]]\n\n==History==\nThe origins of the Indiana University (IU) School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI extend to 1891 when the first class was offered in Indianapolis for credit. That course, in [[economics]], was taught by Indiana University Professor Jeremiah W. Jenks. The course was so successful that IU followed it with classes in history, [[sociology]], and [[English studies|English]]. The program was modeled after the \"extension movement\" pioneered in [[England]] in the 1860s by [[Cambridge University]].<ref>[http://www.liberalarts.iupui.edu Reference]</ref>\n\nDeans of the School of Liberal Arts have included [[Joseph T. Taylor]], [[William M. Plater]], John D. Barlow, [[Herman Saatkamp]], Robert W. White, William Blomquist, and Thomas J. Davis.\n\n==Profile==\nThe School of Liberal Arts, in its current form, took shape in 1972, three years after the consolidation of Indiana University and Purdue University programs in Indianapolis as IUPUI. Today, the School of Liberal Arts has more than 230 full-time faculty. In the School of Liberal Arts, there are approximately 2200 [[undergraduate]] students and 300 [[graduate student]]s. Between 2010 and 2014, Liberal Arts faculty received $27,755,795 in external grants and contracts.<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://liberalarts.iupui.edu/index.php/about|website=Liberal Arts @ IUPUI|accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Academic program==\n[[Hallmarks]] of the School of Liberal Arts are an emphasis on the [[undergraduate]] experience, graduate programs with an applied focus, innovative and creative class offerings and degree programs, small class size and flexible schedules, and the combination of [[theory]] with practical application.\n\n==Liberal Arts Departments, Programs, and Centers==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''Departments'''\n\n*Department of Anthropology\n* Department of Communication Studies\n* Department of Economics\n* Department of English\n* Department of Geography\n* Department of History\n* Department of Journalism and Public Relations\n* Department of Philosophy\n* Department of Political Science\n* Department of Religious Studies\n* Department of Sociology\n* Department of World Languages and Cultures\n\n'''Centers and projects'''\n\n* Center for Economic Education\n* Geography Educators Network of Indiana\n* Indiana Center for Intercultural Communication (ICIC)\n* Institute for American Thought\n** Frederick Douglass Papers\n** Peirce Edition Project\n** Santayana Edition\n** Max Kade German-American Center\n** Center for Ray Bradbury Studies\n** Josiah Royce Edition\n* National Council on Public History\n* The Polis Center\n* Spanish Resource Center\n* Center for the Study of Religion and American Culture\n* Writing Center\n{{col-break}}\n'''Undergraduate programs'''\n\n* Africana Studies (B.A.)\n* American Sign Language/English Interpreting (Cert./B.S.)\n* Anthropology (B.A.)\n* Communication Studies (B.A.)\n* Economics (B.A.)\n* English (B.A.)\n* French (B.A.)\n* General Studies (B.A.)\n* Geographic Information Science (Cert.)\n* Geography (B.A.)\n* German (B.A.)\n* History (B.A.)\n* Human Communication in a Mediated World (Cert.)\n* Journalism (Cert./B.A.)\n* Individualized Major Program (B.A.)\n* International Studies (B.A.)\n* Latino Studies (Cert.)\n* Medical Humanities and Health Studies (B.A.)\n* Motorsports Studies (Cert.)\n* Museum Studies (Cert.)\n* Paralegal Studies (Cert./B.A.)\n* Philosophy (B.A.)\n* Political Science (B.A.)\n* Public Relations (Cert./B.A.)\n* Religious Studies (B.A.)\n* Sociology (B.A.)\n* Spanish (B.A.)\n* Theatre and Performance (Cert.)\n* Translation Studies (Cert.)\n{{col-break}}\n'''Graduate programs'''\n\n* Anthropology (M.A.)\n* Applied Communication (M.A.)\n* Economics (M.A./Ph.D.)\n* English (M.A.)\n* Geographic Information Science (M.S./Grad Cert.)\n* History/Public History (M.A.)\n* Health Communication (Ph.D.)\n* Museum Studies (M.A./Grad Cert.)\n* Philanthropic Studies (M.A./Ph.D.)\n* Philosophy (M.A./Grad Cert.)\n* Political Science (M.A.)\n* Professional Editing (Grad Cert.)\n* Public Relations (M.A.)\n* Sociology (M.A.)\n* Sports Journalism (M.A.)\n* Survey Research (Grad Cert.)\n* Teaching English to Speakers of Other Languages (Grad Cert.)\n* Teaching Spanish (M.A.T.)\n* Teaching Writing (Grad Cert.)\n\n'''Dual Degrees'''\n\n* Economics-Philanthropic Studies (MA/MA)\n* History-Library Science (MA/MLS)\n* History-Philanthropic Studies (MA/MA)\n* Philosophy-Law (MA/JD)\n* Philosophy-Medicine (MA/MD)\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://liberalarts.iupui.edu/ Indiana University School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI]\n*[http://www.iupui.edu Indiana University-Purdue University Indianapolis]\n*[http://www.ulib.iupui.edu/special/collections/uarchives/ua002 School Archives]\n*[http://www.indiana.edu/ Indiana University]\n\n{{IUPUI}}\n{{Public colleges and universities in Indiana}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indiana University School Of Liberal Arts At Iupui}}\n[[Category:Indiana University \u2013 Purdue University Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges at universities in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|image_name = \n|name = Indiana University School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI\n|established = 1972\n|type = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|dean= William Blomquist\n|city = [[Indianapolis, IN|Indianapolis]]\n|state = [[Indiana]]\n|country = [[United States|USA]]\n|coor    = {{coord|39.773741|-86.175239|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|students = 2000\n|faculty= 230\n|website= [http://liberalarts.iupui.edu/ liberalarts.iupui.edu]\n}}\n\n{{Primary sources|date=March 2010}}\nThe '''Indiana University School of Liberal Arts''' is the home of the [[humanities]] and [[social sciences]] at [[Indiana University]]-[[Purdue University]] [[Indianapolis]] (IUPUI), an urban, research [[campus]]. The only [[liberal arts]] school in the Indiana University system, the School of Liberal Arts has 11 departments (Anthropology, Communication Studies, Economics, English, Geography, History, Philosophy, Political Science, Religious Studies, Sociology, and World Languages & Cultures), 16 undergraduate degree programs (including those offered in departmental disciplines as well as American Sign Language/English Interpreting, International Studies, Philanthropic Studies and the Individualized Major Program), and 15 graduate degrees and certificates including Ph.D.s in Economics and Philanthropic Studies. The School of Liberal Arts also houses multiple centers for research and study, some nationally and internationally renowned.\n\n[[File:IUPUI-Cavanaugh-trees.JPG|thumb|Cavanaugh Hall is home to the IU School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI.]]\n\n==History==\nThe origins of the Indiana University (IU) School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI extend to 1891 when the first class was offered in Indianapolis for credit. That course, in [[economics]], was taught by Indiana University Professor Jeremiah W. Jenks. The course was so successful that IU followed it with classes in history, [[sociology]], and [[English studies|English]]. The program was modeled after the \"extension movement\" pioneered in [[England]] in the 1860s by [[Cambridge University]].<ref>[http://www.liberalarts.iupui.edu Reference]</ref>\n\nDeans of the School of Liberal Arts have included [[Joseph T. Taylor]], [[William M. Plater]], John D. Barlow, [[Herman Saatkamp]], Robert W. White, William Blomquist, and Thomas J. Davis.\n\n==Profile==\nThe School of Liberal Arts, in its current form, took shape in 1972, three years after the consolidation of Indiana University and Purdue University programs in Indianapolis as IUPUI. Today, the School of Liberal Arts has more than 230 full-time faculty. In the School of Liberal Arts, there are approximately 2200 [[undergraduate]] students and 300 [[graduate student]]s. Between 2010 and 2014, Liberal Arts faculty received $27,755,795 in external grants and contracts.<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://liberalarts.iupui.edu/index.php/about|website=Liberal Arts @ IUPUI|accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Academic program==\n[[Hallmarks]] of the School of Liberal Arts are an emphasis on the [[undergraduate]] experience, graduate programs with an applied focus, innovative and creative class offerings and degree programs, small class size and flexible schedules, and the combination of [[theory]] with practical application.\n\n==Liberal Arts Departments, Programs, and Centers==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''Departments'''\n\n*Department of Anthropology\n* Department of Communication Studies\n* Department of Economics\n* Department of English\n* Department of Geography\n* Department of History\n* Department of Journalism and Public Relations\n* Department of Philosophy\n* Department of Political Science\n* Department of Religious Studies\n* Department of Sociology\n* Department of World Languages and Cultures\n\n'''Centers and projects'''\n\n* Center for Economic Education\n* Geography Educators Network of Indiana\n* Indiana Center for Intercultural Communication (ICIC)\n* Institute for American Thought\n** Frederick Douglass Papers\n** Peirce Edition Project\n** Santayana Edition\n** Max Kade German-American Center\n** Center for Ray Bradbury Studies\n** Josiah Royce Edition\n* National Council on Public History\n* The Polis Center\n* Spanish Resource Center\n* Center for the Study of Religion and American Culture\n* Writing Center\n{{col-break}}\n'''Undergraduate programs'''\n\n* Africana Studies (B.A.)\n* American Sign Language/English Interpreting (Cert./B.S.)\n* Anthropology (B.A.)\n* Communication Studies (B.A.)\n* Economics (B.A.)\n* English (B.A.)\n* French (B.A.)\n* General Studies (B.A.)\n* Geographic Information Science (Cert.)\n* Geography (B.A.)\n* German (B.A.)\n* History (B.A.)\n* Human Communication in a Mediated World (Cert.)\n* Journalism (Cert./B.A.)\n* Individualized Major Program (B.A.)\n* International Studies (B.A.)\n* Latino Studies (Cert.)\n* Medical Humanities and Health Studies (B.A.)\n* Motorsports Studies (Cert.)\n* Museum Studies (Cert.)\n* Paralegal Studies (Cert./B.A.)\n* Philosophy (B.A.)\n* Political Science (B.A.)\n* Public Relations (Cert./B.A.)\n* Religious Studies (B.A.)\n* Sociology (B.A.)\n* Spanish (B.A.)\n* Theatre and Performance (Cert.)\n* Translation Studies (Cert.)\n{{col-break}}\n'''Graduate programs'''\n\n* Anthropology (M.A.)\n* Applied Communication (M.A.)\n* Economics (M.A./Ph.D.)\n* English (M.A.)\n* Geographic Information Science (M.S./Grad Cert.)\n* History/Public History (M.A.)\n* Health Communication (Ph.D.)\n* Museum Studies (M.A./Grad Cert.)\n* Philanthropic Studies (M.A./Ph.D.)\n* Philosophy (M.A./Grad Cert.)\n* Political Science (M.A.)\n* Professional Editing (Grad Cert.)\n* Public Relations (M.A.)\n* Sociology (M.A.)\n* Sports Journalism (M.A.)\n* Survey Research (Grad Cert.)\n* Teaching English to Speakers of Other Languages (Grad Cert.)\n* Teaching Spanish (M.A.T.)\n* Teaching Writing (Grad Cert.)\n\n'''Dual Degrees'''\n\n* Economics-Philanthropic Studies (MA/MA)\n* History-Library Science (MA/MLS)\n* History-Philanthropic Studies (MA/MA)\n* Philosophy-Law (MA/JD)\n* Philosophy-Medicine (MA/MD)\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://liberalarts.iupui.edu/ Indiana University School of Liberal Arts at IUPUI]\n*[http://www.iupui.edu Indiana University-Purdue University Indianapolis]\n*[http://www.ulib.iupui.edu/special/collections/uarchives/ua002 School Archives]\n*[http://www.indiana.edu/ Indiana University]\n\n{{IUPUI}}\n{{Public colleges and universities in Indiana}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indiana University School Of Liberal Arts At Iupui}}\n[[Category:Indiana University \u2013 Purdue University Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges at universities in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indiana_University_School_of_Liberal_Arts_at_IUPUI"}
{"title_page": "Illinois Wesleyan University", "text_new": "{{About|Illinois Wesleyan University in Bloomington, Illinois, U.S.|a list of other colleges and universities with names including \"Wesleyan\"|Wesleyan University (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Illinois Wesleyan University\n|image= File:Illinois-wesleyan-logo-stacked.png\n|image_size=250px\n|motto = ''Scientia et Sapientia'' ([[Latin]])\n|mottoeng = Knowledge and Wisdom\n|established = 1850\n|type = Private university\n|endowment = $ 222 million (FY 2014)\n|president = [[S. Georgia Nugent]]\n|city = [[Bloomington, Illinois|Bloomington]]\n|state = [[Illinois]]\n|country = United States\n|undergrad = 1,893\n|faculty = 175\n|staff = 300\n|campus = Suburban<br>82 acres (324,000 m\u00b2)\n|nickname = [[Titan (mythology)|Titans]]\n| athletics = \n|sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division III]] \u2013 [[College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin|CCIW]]\n|colors         = Green {{color box|#006633}}\nWhite {{color box|#FFFFFF}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/about/traditions/|title=Traditions &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>|website = [http://www.iwu.edu/ www.iwu.edu]\n}}\n\n'''Illinois Wesleyan University''' is an independent, exclusively [[undergraduate]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] in [[Bloomington, Illinois]]. Founded in 1850, the central portion of the present campus was acquired in 1854 with the first building erected in 1856.\n\n== History ==\n{{Expand section|date=December 2017}}\nThe university was founded in 1850 as a private four-year college in [[Bloomington, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite book|isbn=9780768926903|title=Colleges in the Midwest|publisher=Petersons|year=2009|page=51}}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\nIllinois Wesleyan is an independent, residential, [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts]] university with an approximate enrollment of 1,700.<ref name=\"IWU.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/academics/|title=Academics &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> It offers over 80 majors, minors and programs.<ref name=\"IWU.edu\"/> The university maintains a low student/faculty ratio of 10 to 1, with an average class size of 15<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/about/facts.html|title=Facts &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> Also, more than 9 in 10 IWU students receive a scholarship or need-based assistance.<ref name=\"issuu.com\">{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/illinoiswesleyanuniversity/docs/viewbook|title=Viewbook|website=Issuu}}</ref> Illinois Wesleyan is also a member of the [[Annapolis Group]] and its strong foundations in the liberal arts have earned it chapters in the prestigious [[Phi Beta Kappa]] and [[Phi Kappa Phi]] honor societies.\n\nThe university consists of the College of Liberal Arts, with 17 academic departments; the College of Fine Arts that includes three professional schools\u2014the Ames School of Art, School of Music and the School of Theatre Arts; and the School of Nursing. Illinois Wesleyan's campus occupies approximately {{convert|82|acre|m2}} a short walk north from downtown Bloomington in central Illinois.\n\nIWU's School of Nursing was established in 1959. Applicants apply directly to the School of Nursing and typically graduate in four years with a BSN. The course work emphasizes clinical placement {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} and individualized education {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} and experience.\n\n[[Bachelor's degree]] programs are offered in three colleges:<ref>Illinois Wesleyan University website, \"Degrees and Majors\", accessed 12/06/2007. [http://www2.iwu.edu/academics/departments/ iwu.edu]</ref>\n*College of Liberal Arts: 17 departments and 7 interdisciplinary programs, organized in 1906\n*College of Fine Arts: Schools of art, music, and theatre arts organized in 1929, 1946, 1947 respectively\n*School of Nursing: Established in 1959\n\n===Ames Library===\n[[File:IWU AmesLibrary 1555 2012-10-16.jpg|thumb|The Ames Library]]\nIllinois Wesleyan's Ames Library was completed in 2002. It contains over 368,000 volumes spread over five floors. The Ames Library also houses eight sets of stained glass panels originally from Pembroke College at [[Oxford University]]. Among the special collections are the papers of former U.S. Representative Leslie C. Arends; the Gernon collection of first editions of detective fiction and mysteries; and the Schultz collection of 18th- and 19th-century British drama, including ''[[The Beggar's Opera]]''. Construction cost $25.7 million; Shepley Bulfinch Richardson and Abbot were the principal architects.<ref>[http://www.iwu.edu/library/information/ames_facts.shtml Ames Facts] IWU</ref>\n\n===May Term===\nIllinois Wesleyan offers a May Term course option. The university refers to it as a 4\u20134\u20131 system. This allows any student who has completed a full course-load in either the spring or fall semesters of that academic year to enroll in a May Term class.\n\nMay Term classes last approximately three weeks during the month of May. Students take several hours of instruction in the same course each day for five days each week. This allows the students to immerse themselves in that one topic. At the end of the May Term a student completes the equivalent of a single course during one semester.\n\nMay Term emphasizes curricular experimentation, and also offers an opportunity for service projects, study abroad, and internships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/mellon-center/may-term/|title=May Term &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n===Study abroad===\nIllinois Wesleyan offers a number of study abroad opportunities, and ranks in the top 40 schools in the nation for students studying abroad.<ref>[https://www.iwu.edu/admissions/Why/guides.html], Open Doors Report.</ref> IWU's International Office provides support for over 300 global Study Abroad Options in 70 countries through various institutes such as IES and [[SIT Study Abroad]]. Domestically, IWU offers a UN semester, a Washington Semester, and the Associated Colleges of the Midwest Chicago Program. Internationally it offers programs in London and Barcelona.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwu.edu/studyabroad/choosing/SA_IWUMadrid.shtml|title=IWU.edu|access-date=May 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528155250/http://www.iwu.edu/studyabroad/choosing/SA_IWUMadrid.shtml|archive-date=May 28, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> It also maintains a very strong relationship with [[Pembroke College, Oxford]], and traditionally a few juniors can spend a year there as exchange students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwu.edu/studyabroad/choosing/Pembroke.shtml|title=IWU.edu|access-date=May 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528155149/http://www.iwu.edu/studyabroad/choosing/Pembroke.shtml|archive-date=May 28, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nThe university publishes several different undergraduate research journals in the fields of political science, economics, history, and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/research/|title=Research &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> Perhaps the first of its kind, the ''Undergraduate Economic Review'' is a student-managed, [[open access]] journal that has published original undergraduate content from students in the U.S. and at least 15 other countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.iwu.edu/peer_review_list.html|title=Browse Journals and Peer-Reviewed Series &#124; Digital Commons @ IWU &#124; Illinois Wesleyan University Research|website=digitalcommons.iwu.edu}}</ref> Its \"internal twin\", the ''Park Place Economist'', publishes original work of Economics seniors graduating Illinois Wesleyan University. Articles range from basic topical explorations to focused senior research. All published volumes are available online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/economics/PPE.html|title=The Park Place Economist &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\nThe John Wesley Powell Student Research Conference was established in 1990 to provide opportunities for students to present research projects and findings in a public and interactive manner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/research-conference/|title=John Wesley Powell Research Conference &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> The Action Research Center was established in 2004 to partner student research and service projects with the wider Illinois community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/magazine/2010/spring/ARC.html|title=IWU Magazine - Spring 2010 - Action Research Center &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Athletics ==\n[[File:Shirk-center-spring-31-web-edit.jpg|thumb|Shirk Center at Illinois Wesleyan University]]\nIllinois Wesleyan University participates in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]'s [[NCAA Division III|Division III]] and is a member of the [[College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin]] (CCIW). Illinois Wesleyan teams have won 136 CCIW Titles and 6 Division III National Championships. Illinois Wesleyan has produced 117 Academic All-American student athletes since the program began in 1970, a total that is tied for 13th among all participating colleges and universities, regardless of NCAA division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwusports.com/news/2015/6/22/WTRACK_0622154215.aspx|title=Boudreau Elected First Team Academic All-American\u00ae|website=Illinois Wesleyan University Athletics}}</ref>\n\nIllinois Wesleyan University's Division III athletic teams, known as the \"Titans,\" helped found the College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin (CCIW) in 1946. Illinois Wesleyan was a member of the [[Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference]] from 1910 to 1937.\n\nThe Titans have 22 varsity teams, 11 men's and 11 women's, with the addition of men's and women's lacrosse in 2014 and 2015, respectively.\n\n===Shirk Center===\n[[File:Shirk Center Stitch.jpg|thumb|top|275px|Shirk Center]]\nShirk Center is the university's athletic complex. The two-story {{convert|135000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} complex was constructed in 1994. A 20,000-square-foot expansion was opened in 2016. The Shirk complex provides a multi-use facility for squash, tennis, basketball, and other indoor sports. It also houses Fort Natorium, the university's swimming center, as well as classrooms and a six-lane, 200-meter track.<ref name=\"issuu.com\"/> The Shirk Center also hosted the 2010 & 2011 NCAA Division III Women's National Basketball Championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/sports/basketball-women/d3|title=DIII Women&#039;s College Basketball - Home &#124; NCAA.com|website=www.ncaa.com}}</ref> The \"Shirk\" is also the championship venue for the annual [[State Farm Holiday Classic]], one of the largest, coed high school holiday basketball tournaments in the nation.\n\n===Division III NCAA National championships===\n*Men's\n**Basketball \u2013 1997\n**Baseball \u2013 2010\n**Golf \u2013 2019\n*Women's\n**Indoor Track & Field \u2013 2008\n**Outdoor Track & Field \u2013 2008, 2010, 2016\n**Basketball \u2013 2012\n\n==Campus life==\nThe university and Student Senate regularly bring speakers and comedians to campus. There are regularly organized social events both on and off-campus. {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}   Faculty colloquia regularly provide opportunities for intellectual discussion and encouragement. {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}  The campus itself is an arboretum, home to over 1,000 trees from 90 different species.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/treemap/|title=IWU Tree Map|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n===Residential living and community===\nAll halls are co-ed, all residence hall rooms have cable television and wireless Internet, and the vast majority of rooms are two/three-person units. Dodds Hall offers eight-person suites and Harriet Fuller Rust House offers four-person and six-person suites as well as two eight-person two-story townhouse style suites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwu.edu/aboutiwu/campus/residential/dodds.shtml|title=IWU.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwu.edu/aboutiwu/campus/residential/rust.shtml|title=IWU.edu}}</ref> Traditional style living is offered in Magill Hall and Pfeiffer Hall. First-year students live in first-year halls: Gulick Hall, Munsell Hall, and Ferguson Hall. Illinois Wesleyan also offers two themed housing communities: Kemp Hall (the International House) and Blackstock Hall (the Arts House).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/residential-life/halls/|title=Residence Hall Introduction &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> Nearly one-third of the campus community is involved and/or resides in one of five fraternities or four sororities. Students are also able to live in the Gates (est. 2013), and the East Street Apartments (est. 2006) which are modern, apartment-style residences that students can sign as leases.\n\n===Campus activities and organizations===\nThere are 200 student organizations at Wesleyan, ranging from the rock-climbing club, the Anime club, to [[Pi Kappa Lambda]] (the music honors society).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://php.iwu.edu/clubs/|title=Registered Student Organizations &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=php.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n===Lectures and speakers===\nIllinois Wesleyan co-hosts the annual Stevenson Lecture Series, initiated in 1965 as a memorial to former Governor [[Adlai Stevenson II|Adlai Stevenson]]. IWU co-hosts the Lecture Series with [[Illinois State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.iwu.edu/stevenson_lecture/|title=Stevenson Lecture Series, Illinois Wesleyan University &#124; IWU Special Events &#124; Illinois Wesleyan University|website=digitalcommons.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n[[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] spoke at the university twice, in 1961 and 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/news/GospelFestival.html|title=Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Fellowship Dinner and National Holiday Gospel Festival &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> In 1966 he came to the university while he was trying to organize in Chicago. There, he said,\n\n<blockquote>\nAnd I still have faith in America because I love America and I believe that we will continue to build a coalition of conscience that one day will solve this problem. We sing a little song in our movement and it has been our guiding faith. Sometimes we\u2019ve been facing hooded perpetrators of violence; sometimes we face jeering mobs. Sometimes we face dogs and the gushing waters from fire hoses. Sometimes in crowded jail cells we join hands to sing it. And sometimes in just open mass meetings. But we could sing it as a hymn of faith. We shall overcome, we shall overcome, deep in my heart I do believe we shall overcome.\n<ref>[http://www.iwu.edu/newsrelease06/KingSpeech6.shtml IWU.edu], at Illinois Wesleyan University, courtesy of WJBC, 1966.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n===Media===\nIllinois Wesleyan has its own radio station, WESN 88.1 FM. It plays a mix of indie, rock, classic, electronic, and folk music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wesn.org/|title=WESN|website=wesn.org}}</ref>\n\nWesleyan also has its own television station, Titan TV, broadcasting exclusively to IWU's residence halls.  It broadcasts a collection of movies and campus announcements.\n\nThe campus newspaper is called ''The Argus'', published continuously under student supervision since 1894.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwuargus.com/|title=The Argus|website=The Argus}}</ref>\n\n==Sustainability==\nIWU's Minor Myers, Jr. Welcome Center, opened in 2008, and State Farm Hall, opened in 2013, include geothermal heating/cooling systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/about/initiatives/sustainability.html|title=Sustainability &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> The Welcome Center was awarded Silver Certification as a Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design ([[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]]) building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/photos/tour.html|title=Campus Photo Tour &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\nThe university's \"Think Green\" behavioral change campaign encourages community members to conserve resources.<ref name=\"IWU Efforts to Conserve Resources\">{{cite web\n| title =IWU Efforts to Conserve Resources\n| publisher =Illinois Institute of Technology \n| url =http://digitalcommons.iwu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=green_docs\n| accessdate = 2009-06-08 }}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n* [[Abraham Akaka]], civil rights activist, humanitarian, three decades as shepherd of [[Kawaiaha\u02bbo Church]] in Honolulu, Hawaii\n* [[H. Clarence Baldridge]], [[Governor of Idaho|Governor]] of [[Idaho]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_idaho/col2-content/main-content-list/title_baldridge_h.html|title=Idaho Governor H. Clarence Baldridge|publisher= National Governors Association |accessdate= September 19, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Bisaillon]], wide receiver, [[College Football Hall of Fame]] inductee\n* [[Tony Blazine]], NFL player and [[College Football Hall of Fame]] inductee\n* [[Cherlynlavaughn Bradley]], first African-American woman to earn a PhD in organic chemistry at [[Northwestern University]]\n* [[Bill Brady (politician)|Bill Brady]], Illinois State Senator, 2010 Republican candidate for Governor of Illinois\n* [[J. Bradley Burzynski]], Illinois State Senator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/Senate/Senator.asp?MemberID=978 |title=Illinois General Assembly - Senator Biography |publisher=Ilga.gov |date=1955-07-13 |accessdate=2019-10-20}}</ref>\n* [[Alice Sudduth Byerly]] (1855\u20131904), temperance activist\n* [[Charlene Carruthers]], feminist activist, National Director of Black Youth Project 100\n* [[Kirsten Chambers]], operatic soprano\n* [[Alfred O. Coffin]], first African American man to receive a PhD in Biology\n* [[Alex Cosmidis]], baseball player, scout, minor-league manager\n* [[John E. Cribbet]], legal scholar, Dean of [[University of Illinois College of Law]], and Chancellor of [[University of Illinois]]\n* [[Tom Cross (politician)|Tom Cross]], Illinois State Representative and House Republican Leader\n* [[Bill Damaschke]], head of Creative Production and Development, [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n* [[Amanda Dehnert]], theater director, musician, and writer; artistic director for Trinity Rep in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], RI\n* [[Kevin Dunn]], actor, noted for his appearances in ''Transformers'' movie franchise and TV series ''[[Veep (TV series)|Veep]]''\n* [[Frankie Faison]], actor, noted for his appearance in all four [[Hannibal Lecter]] films\n* [[George L. Fox]], [[Chaplain's Medal for Heroism]] recipient\n* [[James Fulkerson]], composer\n* [[Glen Gray]], bandleader\n* [[Lester Hunt]], [[Governor of Wyoming|Governor]] of [[Wyoming]]\n* [[Richard Jenkins]], Oscar-nominated actor, best known for his roles in ''[[The Visitor (2007 drama film)|The Visitor]]'' and ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'' (2001\u20132005)\n* [[Charles \"Buffalo\" Jones]], [[Western (genre)|Western]] [[bison|buffalo]] hunter who co-founded [[Garden City, Kansas]]; attended for two years ca. 1860 but did not graduate<ref>{{cite web|url=http://h-net.msu.edu/cgi-bin/logbrowse.pl?trx=vx&list=h-shgape&month=0008&week=c&msg=4ZaC2nPza053qdx7jtInAg&user=&pw=|title=Buffalo Jones|publisher=h-net.msu.edu|accessdate=September 4, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306074551/http://h-net.msu.edu/cgi-bin/logbrowse.pl?trx=vx&list=h-shgape&month=0008&week=c&msg=4ZaC2nPza053qdx7jtInAg&user=&pw=|archive-date=March 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Tony Kaska]], football player\n* [[Tariq Khan (pundit)|Tariq Khan]], Fox News Academy Awards expert<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/news/2014/02-khan-on-oscars.html|title=Khan '93 Describes Path to Oscar Punditry &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n* Dave Kindred, columnist for ''[[Washington Post]]'' and ''[[Sporting News]]'', elected to [[NSSA Hall of Fame|National Sportscasters and Sportswriters Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Sigmund Livingston]], founder of [[Anti-Defamation League]]\n* [[Scott W. Lucas]], [[United States Senate|Senator]] of Illinois\n* [[Denny Matthews]], radio voice of [[Kansas City Royals]] since team's inception in 1969, [[Ford Frick Award]] recipient\n* [[Bessie S. McColgin]], Oklahoma legislator, first woman to serve in Oklahoma House of Representatives\n* [[Wayne Messmer]], longtime [[Wrigley Field]] public-address announcer and singer of national anthem\n* [[Jim Molinari]], former head men\u2019s basketball coach at [[Bradley University]] and [[Western Illinois University]] \n* [[Christina Moore]], actress, known for ''[[MADtv]]'' and ''[[90210 (TV series)|90210]]''\n* [[Bob Morrow (American football)|Bob Morrow]], [[NFL]] player<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MorrBo22.htm|title=Bob Morrow Stats|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref>\n* [[Gregory Poland]], physician and vaccinologist\n* [[Doug Rader]], Major League Baseball player and manager\n* [[George Rock]], band member with [[Spike Jones]] and His City Slickers\n* [[Edward B. Rust, Jr.]], CEO of State Farm\n* [[Larry Shue]], playwright and actor\n* [[Jack Sikma]], seven-time [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] All-Star center and Hall of Fame inductee<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/s/sikmaja01.html|title=Jack Sikma Stats|website=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n* [[Ralph C. Smedley]], founder of [[Toastmasters International]]\n* [[Sandra Steingraber]], author and [[biologist]] \n* Thomas Sterling, [[United States Congressman]], graduated from IWU in 1875; served in Congress 1913\u20131925\n* [[Margaret Ashmore Sudduth]] (1859\u20131957), educator, editor, temperance advocate\n* [[Dawn Upshaw]], [[Grammy Award]]-winning [[soprano]]\n* [[Bobby Winkles]], Major League Baseball manager and College Baseball Hall of Fame coach\n* [[Steve Yoder]], college basketball coach\n\n==Notable faculty==\n*[[John Marshall Hamilton]], [[Governor of Illinois]]\n*[[Judy Jolley Mohraz]], history lecturer 1972\u20131974, 9th president of [[Goucher College]]\n*[[Tari Renner]], political science professor,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/political-science/faculty/TariRenner.html|title=Tari Renner &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> Mayor of Bloomington, IL<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cityblm.org/government/city-council/city-council-info/tari-renner|title=Tari Renner &#124; City of Bloomington, Illinois|website=www.cityblm.org}}</ref>\n*[[Elmo Scott Watson]], journalism professor, 1947\u20131950, specialist on the [[American Midwest]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Illinois Wesleyan University}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.iwu.edu}}\n*[http://www.iwusports.com/ Official athletics website]\n*{{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Illinois Wesleyan University |short=x}}\n\n{{College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin navbox}}\n{{MethodistColleges}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n\n{{Coord|40|29|26|N|88|59|29|W|format=dms|display=title|type:edu_region:US-IL}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Illinois Wesleyan University| ]]\n[[Category:1850 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1850]]\n[[Category:Bloomington, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Bloomington\u2013Normal]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|Illinois Wesleyan University in Bloomington, Illinois, U.S.|a list of other colleges and universities with names including \"Wesleyan\"|Wesleyan University (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Illinois Wesleyan University\n|image= File:Illinois-wesleyan-logo-stacked.png\n|image_size=250px\n|motto = ''Scientia et Sapientia'' ([[Latin]])\n|mottoeng = Knowledge and Wisdom\n|established = 1850\n|type = Private university\n|endowment = $ 222 million (FY 2014)\n|president = [[S. Georgia Nugent]]\n|city = [[Bloomington, Illinois|Bloomington]]\n|state = [[Illinois]]\n|country = United States\n|undergrad = 1,893\n|faculty = 175\n|staff = 300\n|campus = Suburban<br>82 acres (324,000 m\u00b2)\n|nickname = [[Titan (mythology)|Titans]]\n| athletics = \n|sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division III]] \u2013 [[College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin|CCIW]]\n|colors         = Green {{color box|#006633}}\nWhite {{color box|#FFFFFF}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/about/traditions/|title=Traditions &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>|website = [http://www.iwu.edu/ www.iwu.edu]\n}}\n\n'''Illinois Wesleyan University''' is an independent, exclusively [[undergraduate]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] in [[Bloomington, Illinois]]. Founded in 1850, the central portion of the present campus was acquired in 1854 with the first building erected in 1856.\n\n== History ==\n{{Expand section|date=December 2017}}\nThe university was founded in 1850 as a private four-year college in [[Bloomington, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite book|isbn=9780768926903|title=Colleges in the Midwest|publisher=Petersons|year=2009|page=51}}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\nIllinois Wesleyan is an independent, residential, [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts]] university with an approximate enrollment of 1,700.<ref name=\"IWU.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/academics/|title=Academics &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> It offers over 80 majors, minors and programs.<ref name=\"IWU.edu\"/> The university maintains a low student/faculty ratio of 10 to 1, with an average class size of 15<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/about/facts.html|title=Facts &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> Also, more than 9 in 10 IWU students receive a scholarship or need-based assistance.<ref name=\"issuu.com\">{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/illinoiswesleyanuniversity/docs/viewbook|title=Viewbook|website=Issuu}}</ref> Illinois Wesleyan is also a member of the [[Annapolis Group]] and its strong foundations in the liberal arts have earned it chapters in the prestigious [[Phi Beta Kappa]] and [[Phi Kappa Phi]] honor societies.\n\nThe university consists of the College of Liberal Arts, with 17 academic departments; the College of Fine Arts that includes three professional schools\u2014the Ames School of Art, School of Music and the School of Theatre Arts; and the School of Nursing. Illinois Wesleyan's campus occupies approximately {{convert|82|acre|m2}} a short walk north from downtown Bloomington in central Illinois.\n\nIWU's School of Nursing was established in 1959. Applicants apply directly to the School of Nursing and typically graduate in four years with a BSN. The course work emphasizes clinical placement {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} and individualized education {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} and experience.\n\n[[Bachelor's degree]] programs are offered in three colleges:<ref>Illinois Wesleyan University website, \"Degrees and Majors\", accessed 12/06/2007. [http://www2.iwu.edu/academics/departments/ iwu.edu]</ref>\n*College of Liberal Arts: 17 departments and 7 interdisciplinary programs, organized in 1906\n*College of Fine Arts: Schools of art, music, and theatre arts organized in 1929, 1946, 1947 respectively\n*School of Nursing: Established in 1959\n\n===Ames Library===\n[[File:IWU AmesLibrary 1555 2012-10-16.jpg|thumb|The Ames Library]]\nIllinois Wesleyan's Ames Library was completed in 2002. It contains over 368,000 volumes spread over five floors. The Ames Library also houses eight sets of stained glass panels originally from Pembroke College at [[Oxford University]]. Among the special collections are the papers of former U.S. Representative Leslie C. Arends; the Gernon collection of first editions of detective fiction and mysteries; and the Schultz collection of 18th- and 19th-century British drama, including ''[[The Beggar's Opera]]''. Construction cost $25.7 million; Shepley Bulfinch Richardson and Abbot were the principal architects.<ref>[http://www.iwu.edu/library/information/ames_facts.shtml Ames Facts] IWU</ref>\n\n===May Term===\nIllinois Wesleyan offers a May Term course option. The university refers to it as a 4\u20134\u20131 system. This allows any student who has completed a full course-load in either the spring or fall semesters of that academic year to enroll in a May Term class.\n\nMay Term classes last approximately three weeks during the month of May. Students take several hours of instruction in the same course each day for five days each week. This allows the students to immerse themselves in that one topic. At the end of the May Term a student completes the equivalent of a single course during one semester.\n\nMay Term emphasizes curricular experimentation, and also offers an opportunity for service projects, study abroad, and internships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/mellon-center/may-term/|title=May Term &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n===Study abroad===\nIllinois Wesleyan offers a number of study abroad opportunities, and ranks in the top 40 schools in the nation for students studying abroad.<ref>[https://www.iwu.edu/admissions/Why/guides.html], Open Doors Report.</ref> IWU's International Office provides support for over 300 global Study Abroad Options in 70 countries through various institutes such as IES and [[SIT Study Abroad]]. Domestically, IWU offers a UN semester, a Washington Semester, and the Associated Colleges of the Midwest Chicago Program. Internationally it offers programs in London and Barcelona.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwu.edu/studyabroad/choosing/SA_IWUMadrid.shtml|title=IWU.edu|access-date=May 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528155250/http://www.iwu.edu/studyabroad/choosing/SA_IWUMadrid.shtml|archive-date=May 28, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> It also maintains a very strong relationship with [[Pembroke College, Oxford]], and traditionally a few juniors can spend a year there as exchange students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwu.edu/studyabroad/choosing/Pembroke.shtml|title=IWU.edu|access-date=May 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528155149/http://www.iwu.edu/studyabroad/choosing/Pembroke.shtml|archive-date=May 28, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nThe university publishes several different undergraduate research journals in the fields of political science, economics, history, and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/research/|title=Research &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> Perhaps the first of its kind, the ''Undergraduate Economic Review'' is a student-managed, [[open access]] journal that has published original undergraduate content from students in the U.S. and at least 15 other countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.iwu.edu/peer_review_list.html|title=Browse Journals and Peer-Reviewed Series &#124; Digital Commons @ IWU &#124; Illinois Wesleyan University Research|website=digitalcommons.iwu.edu}}</ref> Its \"internal twin\", the ''Park Place Economist'', publishes original work of Economics seniors graduating Illinois Wesleyan University. Articles range from basic topical explorations to focused senior research. All published volumes are available online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/economics/PPE.html|title=The Park Place Economist &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\nThe John Wesley Powell Student Research Conference was established in 1990 to provide opportunities for students to present research projects and findings in a public and interactive manner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/research-conference/|title=John Wesley Powell Research Conference &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> The Action Research Center was established in 2004 to partner student research and service projects with the wider Illinois community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/magazine/2010/spring/ARC.html|title=IWU Magazine - Spring 2010 - Action Research Center &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Athletics ==\n[[File:Shirk-center-spring-31-web-edit.jpg|thumb|Shirk Center at Illinois Wesleyan University]]\nIllinois Wesleyan University participates in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]'s [[NCAA Division III|Division III]] and is a member of the [[College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin]] (CCIW). Illinois Wesleyan teams have won 136 CCIW Titles and 6 Division III National Championships. Illinois Wesleyan has produced 117 Academic All-American student athletes since the program began in 1970, a total that is tied for 13th among all participating colleges and universities, regardless of NCAA division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwusports.com/news/2015/6/22/WTRACK_0622154215.aspx|title=Boudreau Elected First Team Academic All-American\u00ae|website=Illinois Wesleyan University Athletics}}</ref>\n\nIllinois Wesleyan University's Division III athletic teams, known as the \"Titans,\" helped found the College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin (CCIW) in 1946. Illinois Wesleyan was a member of the [[Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference]] from 1910 to 1937.\n\nThe Titans have 22 varsity teams, 11 men's and 11 women's, with the addition of men's and women's lacrosse in 2014 and 2015, respectively.\n\n===Shirk Center===\n[[File:Shirk Center Stitch.jpg|thumb|top|275px|Shirk Center]]\nShirk Center is the university's athletic complex. The two-story {{convert|135000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} complex was constructed in 1994. A 20,000-square-foot expansion was opened in 2016. The Shirk complex provides a multi-use facility for squash, tennis, basketball, and other indoor sports. It also houses Fort Natorium, the university's swimming center, as well as classrooms and a six-lane, 200-meter track.<ref name=\"issuu.com\"/> The Shirk Center also hosted the 2010 & 2011 NCAA Division III Women's National Basketball Championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/sports/basketball-women/d3|title=DIII Women&#039;s College Basketball - Home &#124; NCAA.com|website=www.ncaa.com}}</ref> The \"Shirk\" is also the championship venue for the annual [[State Farm Holiday Classic]], one of the largest, coed high school holiday basketball tournaments in the nation.\n\n===Division III NCAA National championships===\n*Men's\n**Basketball \u2013 1997\n**Baseball \u2013 2010\n**Golf \u2013 2019\n\n*Women's\n**Indoor Track & Field \u2013 2008\n**Outdoor Track & Field \u2013 2008, 2010, 2016\n**Basketball \u2013 2012\n\n==Campus life==\nThe university and Student Senate regularly bring speakers and comedians to campus. There are regularly organized social events both on and off-campus. {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}   Faculty colloquia regularly provide opportunities for intellectual discussion and encouragement. {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}  The campus itself is an arboretum, home to over 1,000 trees from 90 different species.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/treemap/|title=IWU Tree Map|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n===Residential living and community===\nAll halls are co-ed, all residence hall rooms have cable television and wireless Internet, and the vast majority of rooms are two/three-person units. Dodds Hall offers eight-person suites and Harriet Fuller Rust House offers four-person and six-person suites as well as two eight-person two-story townhouse style suites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwu.edu/aboutiwu/campus/residential/dodds.shtml|title=IWU.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwu.edu/aboutiwu/campus/residential/rust.shtml|title=IWU.edu}}</ref> Traditional style living is offered in Magill Hall and Pfeiffer Hall. First-year students live in first-year halls: Gulick Hall, Munsell Hall, and Ferguson Hall. Illinois Wesleyan also offers two themed housing communities: Kemp Hall (the International House) and Blackstock Hall (the Arts House).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/residential-life/halls/|title=Residence Hall Introduction &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> Nearly one-third of the campus community is involved and/or resides in one of five fraternities or four sororities. Students are also able to live in the Gates (est. 2013), and the East Street Apartments (est. 2006) which are modern, apartment-style residences that students can sign as leases.\n\n===Campus activities and organizations===\nThere are 200 student organizations at Wesleyan, ranging from the rock-climbing club, the Anime club, to [[Pi Kappa Lambda]] (the music honors society).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://php.iwu.edu/clubs/|title=Registered Student Organizations &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=php.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n===Lectures and speakers===\nIllinois Wesleyan co-hosts the annual Stevenson Lecture Series, initiated in 1965 as a memorial to former Governor [[Adlai Stevenson II|Adlai Stevenson]]. IWU co-hosts the Lecture Series with [[Illinois State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.iwu.edu/stevenson_lecture/|title=Stevenson Lecture Series, Illinois Wesleyan University &#124; IWU Special Events &#124; Illinois Wesleyan University|website=digitalcommons.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\n[[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] spoke at the university twice, in 1961 and 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/news/GospelFestival.html|title=Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Fellowship Dinner and National Holiday Gospel Festival &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> In 1966 he came to the university while he was trying to organize in Chicago. There, he said,\n\n<blockquote>\nAnd I still have faith in America because I love America and I believe that we will continue to build a coalition of conscience that one day will solve this problem. We sing a little song in our movement and it has been our guiding faith. Sometimes we\u2019ve been facing hooded perpetrators of violence; sometimes we face jeering mobs. Sometimes we face dogs and the gushing waters from fire hoses. Sometimes in crowded jail cells we join hands to sing it. And sometimes in just open mass meetings. But we could sing it as a hymn of faith. We shall overcome, we shall overcome, deep in my heart I do believe we shall overcome.\n<ref>[http://www.iwu.edu/newsrelease06/KingSpeech6.shtml IWU.edu], at Illinois Wesleyan University, courtesy of WJBC, 1966.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n===Media===\nIllinois Wesleyan has its own radio station, WESN 88.1 FM. It plays a mix of indie, rock, classic, electronic, and folk music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wesn.org/|title=WESN|website=wesn.org}}</ref>\n\nWesleyan also has its own television station, Titan TV, broadcasting exclusively to IWU's residence halls.  It broadcasts a collection of movies and campus announcements.\n\nThe campus newspaper is called ''The Argus'', published continuously under student supervision since 1894.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwuargus.com/|title=The Argus|website=The Argus}}</ref>\n\n==Sustainability==\nIWU's Minor Myers, Jr. Welcome Center, opened in 2008, and State Farm Hall, opened in 2013, include geothermal heating/cooling systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/about/initiatives/sustainability.html|title=Sustainability &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> The Welcome Center was awarded Silver Certification as a Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design ([[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]]) building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/photos/tour.html|title=Campus Photo Tour &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n\nThe university's \"Think Green\" behavioral change campaign encourages community members to conserve resources.<ref name=\"IWU Efforts to Conserve Resources\">{{cite web\n| title =IWU Efforts to Conserve Resources\n| publisher =Illinois Institute of Technology \n| url =http://digitalcommons.iwu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=green_docs\n| accessdate = 2009-06-08 }}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n* [[Abraham Akaka]], civil rights activist, humanitarian, three decades as shepherd of [[Kawaiaha\u02bbo Church]] in Honolulu, Hawaii\n* [[H. Clarence Baldridge]], [[Governor of Idaho|Governor]] of [[Idaho]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_idaho/col2-content/main-content-list/title_baldridge_h.html|title=Idaho Governor H. Clarence Baldridge|publisher= National Governors Association |accessdate= September 19, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Bisaillon]], wide receiver, [[College Football Hall of Fame]] inductee\n* [[Tony Blazine]], NFL player and [[College Football Hall of Fame]] inductee\n* [[Cherlynlavaughn Bradley]], first African-American woman to earn a PhD in organic chemistry at [[Northwestern University]]\n* [[Bill Brady (politician)|Bill Brady]], Illinois State Senator, 2010 Republican candidate for Governor of Illinois\n* [[J. Bradley Burzynski]], Illinois State Senator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/Senate/Senator.asp?MemberID=978 |title=Illinois General Assembly - Senator Biography |publisher=Ilga.gov |date=1955-07-13 |accessdate=2019-10-20}}</ref>\n* [[Alice Sudduth Byerly]] (1855\u20131904), temperance activist\n* [[Charlene Carruthers]], feminist activist, National Director of Black Youth Project 100\n* [[Kirsten Chambers]], operatic soprano\n* [[Alfred O. Coffin]], first African American man to receive a PhD in Biology\n* [[Alex Cosmidis]], baseball player, scout, minor-league manager\n* [[John E. Cribbet]], legal scholar, Dean of [[University of Illinois College of Law]], and Chancellor of [[University of Illinois]]\n* [[Tom Cross (politician)|Tom Cross]], Illinois State Representative and House Republican Leader\n* [[Bill Damaschke]], head of Creative Production and Development, [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n* [[Amanda Dehnert]], theater director, musician, and writer; artistic director for Trinity Rep in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], RI\n* [[Kevin Dunn]], actor, noted for his appearances in ''Transformers'' movie franchise and TV series ''[[Veep (TV series)|Veep]]''\n* [[Frankie Faison]], actor, noted for his appearance in all four [[Hannibal Lecter]] films\n* [[George L. Fox]], [[Chaplain's Medal for Heroism]] recipient\n* [[James Fulkerson]], composer\n* [[Glen Gray]], bandleader\n* [[Lester Hunt]], [[Governor of Wyoming|Governor]] of [[Wyoming]]\n* [[Richard Jenkins]], Oscar-nominated actor, best known for his roles in ''[[The Visitor (2007 drama film)|The Visitor]]'' and ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'' (2001\u20132005)\n* [[Charles \"Buffalo\" Jones]], [[Western (genre)|Western]] [[bison|buffalo]] hunter who co-founded [[Garden City, Kansas]]; attended for two years ca. 1860 but did not graduate<ref>{{cite web|url=http://h-net.msu.edu/cgi-bin/logbrowse.pl?trx=vx&list=h-shgape&month=0008&week=c&msg=4ZaC2nPza053qdx7jtInAg&user=&pw=|title=Buffalo Jones|publisher=h-net.msu.edu|accessdate=September 4, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306074551/http://h-net.msu.edu/cgi-bin/logbrowse.pl?trx=vx&list=h-shgape&month=0008&week=c&msg=4ZaC2nPza053qdx7jtInAg&user=&pw=|archive-date=March 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Tony Kaska]], football player\n* [[Tariq Khan (pundit)|Tariq Khan]], Fox News Academy Awards expert<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/news/2014/02-khan-on-oscars.html|title=Khan '93 Describes Path to Oscar Punditry &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref>\n* Dave Kindred, columnist for ''[[Washington Post]]'' and ''[[Sporting News]]'', elected to [[NSSA Hall of Fame|National Sportscasters and Sportswriters Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Sigmund Livingston]], founder of [[Anti-Defamation League]]\n* [[Scott W. Lucas]], [[United States Senate|Senator]] of Illinois\n* [[Denny Matthews]], radio voice of [[Kansas City Royals]] since team's inception in 1969, [[Ford Frick Award]] recipient\n* [[Bessie S. McColgin]], Oklahoma legislator, first woman to serve in Oklahoma House of Representatives\n* [[Wayne Messmer]], longtime [[Wrigley Field]] public-address announcer and singer of national anthem\n* [[Jim Molinari]], former head men\u2019s basketball coach at [[Bradley University]] and [[Western Illinois University]] \n* [[Christina Moore]], actress, known for ''[[MADtv]]'' and ''[[90210 (TV series)|90210]]''\n* [[Bob Morrow (American football)|Bob Morrow]], [[NFL]] player<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MorrBo22.htm|title=Bob Morrow Stats|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref>\n* [[Gregory Poland]], physician and vaccinologist\n* [[Doug Rader]], Major League Baseball player and manager\n* [[George Rock]], band member with [[Spike Jones]] and His City Slickers\n* [[Edward B. Rust, Jr.]], CEO of State Farm\n* [[Larry Shue]], playwright and actor\n* [[Jack Sikma]], seven-time [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] All-Star center and Hall of Fame inductee<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/s/sikmaja01.html|title=Jack Sikma Stats|website=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n* [[Ralph C. Smedley]], founder of [[Toastmasters International]]\n* [[Sandra Steingraber]], author and [[biologist]] \n* Thomas Sterling, [[United States Congressman]], graduated from IWU in 1875; served in Congress 1913\u20131925\n* [[Margaret Ashmore Sudduth]] (1859\u20131957), educator, editor, temperance advocate\n* [[Dawn Upshaw]], [[Grammy Award]]-winning [[soprano]]\n* [[Bobby Winkles]], Major League Baseball manager and College Baseball Hall of Fame coach\n* [[Steve Yoder]], college basketball coach\n\n==Notable faculty==\n*[[John Marshall Hamilton]], [[Governor of Illinois]]\n*[[Judy Jolley Mohraz]], history lecturer 1972\u20131974, 9th president of [[Goucher College]]\n*[[Tari Renner]], political science professor,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwu.edu/political-science/faculty/TariRenner.html|title=Tari Renner &#124; Illinois Wesleyan|website=www.iwu.edu}}</ref> Mayor of Bloomington, IL<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cityblm.org/government/city-council/city-council-info/tari-renner|title=Tari Renner &#124; City of Bloomington, Illinois|website=www.cityblm.org}}</ref>\n*[[Elmo Scott Watson]], journalism professor, 1947\u20131950, specialist on the [[American Midwest]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Illinois Wesleyan University}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.iwu.edu}}\n*[http://www.iwusports.com/ Official athletics website]\n*{{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Illinois Wesleyan University |short=x}}\n\n{{College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin navbox}}\n{{MethodistColleges}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n\n{{Coord|40|29|26|N|88|59|29|W|format=dms|display=title|type:edu_region:US-IL}}\n\n[[Category:Illinois Wesleyan University| ]]\n[[Category:1850 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1850]]\n[[Category:Bloomington, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Bloomington\u2013Normal]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Illinois_Wesleyan_University"}
